{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539780"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:46:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:46:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16701"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16701","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16701"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.04,0.1,0.27,0.3]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9392"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107074"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9392"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16701"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89538"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1770"},{"type":"tags","id":"1803"},{"type":"tags","id":"8054"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22210"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39693"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107074"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of mild eye irritation and a yellow spot on the white of her right eye. She works as a gardener and spends most of her day outdoors though dislikes wearing hats or sunglasses. She denies any trauma to the eye, not any weight loss or fatigue. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a raised, yellowish lesion on the nasal conjunctiva of her right eye, not extending onto the cornea (image). The lesion is slightly inflamed but there is no discharge. Visual acuity is 6/6 in both eyes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Surgical excision","Topical antibiotics","Topical corticosteroids","Artificial tears","Observation only"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a typical pinguecula, which is a very common, benign elevation of the conjunctiva caused by degenerative changes related to chronic ultraviolet light exposure. The location (nasal conjunctiva), appearance (raised, yellowish lesion), and association with outdoor work (exposure to dust and wind) are characteristic features.  They are often assymptomatic as cosmetic changes, or can cause mild irritation or itching of the eye.  \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArtificial tears\u003C/strong\u003E are the most appropriate first-line treatment for symptomatic pinguecula. They help reduce irritation by keeping the eye surface lubricated and protecting the elevated lesion from environmental factors. The patient can continue their normal activities while using artificial tears as needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical corticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E would be excessive for initial management of a pinguecula. While they might reduce inflammation, their long-term use carries risks including increased intraocular pressure and cataract formation. They should be reserved for cases with significant inflammation not responding to conservative measures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical excision\u003C/strong\u003E is rarely necessary and would be considered only if the pinguecula causes persistent symptoms despite conservative management, interferes with contact lens wear, or presents significant cosmetic concerns. This patient\u0027s symptoms are mild and can be managed conservatively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated as there is no evidence of infection. Pinguecula is a degenerative condition of the conjunctiva, not an infectious process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation only\u003C/strong\u003E without treatment would be insufficient given the patient\u0027s symptoms of irritation. While pinguecula often requires no treatment, this patient\u0027s symptoms warrant active management with artificial tears.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrevention is also important - the patient should be advised to wear UV-protective sunglasses and a hat with a brim when outdoors to prevent progression of the condition.  It is likely to progress slowly over time.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pinguecula is a benign, yellowish elevation on the conjunctiva that rarely requires treatment unless symptomatic.","Artificial tears and lubricants are first-line treatment for mild irritation from pinguecula."],"references":["Mudhar HS. Update on conjunctival pathology. Indian J Ophthalmol. 2017;65(9):797-807. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5621260/","Al-Hashimi S et al. Pinguecula. American Academy of Opthalmology EyeWiki. 2024. Available at: https://eyewiki.org/Pinguecula#Surgery"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89538"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16701"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21937"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21937"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/17WKzAxRCveyaNhkrootMQU9W2QiX5.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/17WKzAxRCveyaNhkrootMQU9W2QiX5.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":343}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89538"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-25T00:58:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-01T10:15:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9392"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107074"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"sel